text: AS9110C Quality Management System 1 AS9110C Quality Management System Introduction Information below will cover following topics: • Quality Management System (QMS) • Support • Context of the Organization • Operation • Leadership • Performance Evaluation • Planning • Improvement AS9110 is a quality management standard for organizations working in the aviation, space, and defense industries, specifically developed for Aviation Maintenance Organizations, other words, organizations whose primary

business is providing maintenance, repair, and overhaul services for aviation sector products. AS9110 is tailored for organizations with National Airworthiness Authority (NAA) repair station certification, but is also suitable for non-certificated organizations, including those that provide maintenance, repair, and overhaul services for military aviation products. The standard is also intended to be used by organizations with maintenance, repair, and overhaul operations that operate

autonomously, or that are substantially different from their manufacturing operations. The standard sets a common structure with specific documentation, methods, and programs that will improve quality, reduce cost, and guide leadership when implementing precise quality details. AS9110 was prepared by the International Aerospace Quality Group (IAQG) whose goal was to reduce costs and improve quality throughout the aviation industry. This standard can be applied at all levels throughout the supply

chain, maintenance, and commercial aerospace operations. Quality Management System (QMS) A Quality Management System (QMS) is defined as a formalized system that documents processes, procedures, and responsibilities for achieving quality policies and objectives. ISO 9001:2015, the international standard specifying requirements for quality management systems, is the most prominent approach to developing quality systems in the aviation, space, and defense sectors. Term "QMS" sometime is used to

describe the ISO 9001 standard or the group of documents detailing the QMS, it refers to the entirety of the system. AS9110C Quality Management System 2 The QMS manual is typically developed by top management with input from all levels of the organization and typically includes: • The quality policy • Identification of quality processes • The scope of the quality system • Management expectations and responsibilities A Quality Manual gives guidance and direction to an organization’s personnel,

but also gives inspectors or auditors abroad overview of their quality program. Structure of QMS Documentation A common structure of a QMS is much like a pyramid with four levels, each representing a specific area of the system. 1. Quality Manual. Quality methodology defined and rules of the system described. Defines responsibility. 2. Process and Policy Procedures. Defines specific aspects of the general operating procedures – Who, What, and When, “Things” happen. Procedures should include

purpose, scope, responsibilities, records, document control, activities. 3. Lower-level procedural instructions. Step by step instructions for performing tasks associated with the QMS for each area of responsibility. 4. Forms and Records. The forms used in the process. Drawings and/or specifications used in manufacturing or other segments of the process, i.e., inspection, shipping, accounting, etc. Documents Required by a Typical QMS System The AS9110 standard includes several mandatory

documents and records. AS9110C does NOT contain specific requirements for using forms. Benefits of AS9110 Policies and Procedures Each procedure defined in the quality manual should contain policy, purpose, scope, responsibilities, definitions, references and clear-cut, step-by-step instructions for activities including any detailed procedure, supporting form, checklist. It also must include job descriptions necessary to simplify job training, maintain consistency, conforming to standards,

eliminate staff excuses, reduce cost. High Level Structure of QMS The High-Level Structure (HLS) is a set of 10 clauses that all AS & ISO management system standards are required to use. 10 clauses of the HLS, which include scope, normative references, terms and definitions, context of the organization, leadership, planning, support, operation, performance evaluation, improvement. AS9110C Quality Management System 3 One aspect of the HLS that improves project management and quality outcomes is a

focus on the PDCA (plan-do-check-act). Context of the Organization (Clause 4) Context of the Organization is about understanding all the components of the business. Context of the Organization is split into four sections: 4.1 Understanding the organization and its context. 4.2 Understanding the needs and expectations of interested parties. 4.3 Determining the scope of the quality management system. 4.4 Quality Management Systems and its processes. Leadership (Clause 5) Leadership involves

motivating one or more individuals to work towards a common goal. In a business setting, this involves leading and guiding staff and colleagues with a strategy or a plan to meet the business needs of the company. Leaders need to fully engage in the process to achieve the benefits of the QMS. The organization’s leaders must establish, implement, and maintain a quality policy that: 1. Is appropriate to the context of the organization. 2. Provides a framework for setting objectives. 3. Include a

commitment to satisfy applicable requirements. 4. Includes a commitment to continually improve the process. Planning (Clause 6) Planning is the act of conceptualizing activities and procedures to achieve a desired outcome. It involves considering the risks involved and planning accordingly. The identified risks may be at the strategic levels or operational levels. Once all operational and strategic risks have been identified the next step is to plan actions to either reduce the likelihood of its

occurrence (mitigation) and/or reduce the severity or impact of the risk (contingency). The next stage of Planning is to set quality objectives for various levels/functions in the organization. A simple method of establishing quality objectives is using the S.M.A.R.T. methodology that recommends all objectives shall be defined that is Specific, Measurable, Achievable, Relevant, Time-bound. Support (Clause 7) Once the context, commitment, and planning are complete, organizations will have to look

at the support needed to meet goals and objectives. AS9110C Quality Management System 4 Clause 7 specifically talks about People, Infrastructure, Environment for operation of processes, Monitoring and Measuring Resources, Organizational Knowledge, Competence, Awareness, Communication, and Documented Information as support resources that shall be determined, and their effectiveness evaluated to ensure that the organization deliver high-quality product and services and meet the customer

requirements always. This clause requires that the organization plan to ensure that all personnel are aware of the quality policy, quality objectives, and the Quality Management System. Operation (Clause 8) Clause 8 defines requirements for some key processes required to run business. Most of the QMS process related requirements are found here. This single clause includes the processes for: • Customer Communication and Managing Customer Requirements • Design and Development • Managing External

Providers • Production and Service Provision Performance Evaluation (Clause 9) The Performance Evaluation clause defines the requirements to evaluate the performance of the Quality Management System processes to ensure goals are being met. Clause 9 specifies the below mentioned key requirements which are to be met for an effective performance evaluation: • How, when, and what results will be monitored and measured? • Which methods are to be adopted for monitoring and evaluating customer

satisfaction? • Is an efficient internal audit system in place? • Is the QMS being reviewed by Management at planned intervals? Improvements (Clause 10) Clause 10 is all about continually improving the QMS and identifying areas needed for improvement. There are three sections included: • General • Nonconformity and corrective action • Continual improvement
